Aim : To assist Client X to improve their motor portfolio performance¶

Client X is a mid-sized insurer in Asian market where motor is the main line of business.¶

EDA¶

Aim : Why are some values null corresponding to our Cancellation_Date attribute .¶

Assumption :¶

Cancellation Date for a policy can be associated with Two Scenarios¶

  • Scenario A : Policy allowed to expire ( Cancellation Date == Policy End Date == Auto Cancelled == Null Values)

  • Scenario B : Policy cancelled by Client X or by the insured person

In [17]:
print('Scenario A : Policies allowed to expire:', policies['CANCELLATION_DATE'].isnull().sum() + len(policies[policies['CANCELLATION_DATE'] == policies['POLICY_END_DATE']])) 

Scenario A : Policies allowed to expire: 2770800

Feature Engineering for Policies Dataset¶

Aim : Perform Feature Engineering to create a new column Cancellation Rate¶

In [25]:
filter1 = policies['CANCELLATION_DATE']< policies['POLICY_END_DATE']
filter2 = policies['CANCELLATION_DATE']> policies['POLICY_START_DATE']
cancelled_policies_by_branch = policies.where(filter1 & filter2).dropna()['POLICY_WRITTEN_BRANCH'].value_counts().to_frame().rename(columns={'POLICY_WRITTEN_BRANCH':'Total_Cancelled_Policies'})
policies_written_by_branch = policies['POLICY_WRITTEN_BRANCH'].value_counts().to_frame().rename(columns={'POLICY_WRITTEN_BRANCH':'Total_Policies_Written'})
In [26]:
Cancellation_Table = pd.merge(cancelled_policies_by_branch,policies_written_by_branch,left_index=True,right_index=True)
Cancellation_Table['Cancellation_Rate'] = Cancellation_Table['Total_Cancelled_Policies'] /Cancellation_Table['Total_Policies_Written']
In [27]:
Cancellation_Table.sort_values(by='Cancellation_Rate',ascending=False).head()
Out[27]:

Conclusion : Branch 123 , 122, 120 , 116 are the branches having the highest cancellation rate . At the same time the total number of policies written by these branches are minimal comapred to other branches .

We can therefore state that these branches are either new branches that are taking some time to scale and adapt to the situation or they might be operationally inefficient.

Aim : Bucketing the Product Varibale to reduce the cardinality and checking for the avg GWP¶

In [28]:
def set_scr(policies):
    if policies['PRODUCT'] == 'COMMERCIAL MOTOR MISCELLANEOUS VEHICLES':
        return 'Commercial'
    if policies['PRODUCT'] == 'COMMERCIAL MOTOR PASSENGER CARRYING':
        return 'Commercial'
    if policies['PRODUCT'] == 'COMMERCIAL MOTOR GOODS CARRYING':
        return 'Commercial'
    if policies['PRODUCT'] == 'PRIVATE MOTOR 3 & 4 WHEELER':
        return 'Private'
    if policies['PRODUCT'] == 'PRIVATE MOTOR 2 WHEELER':
        return 'Private'
    if policies['PRODUCT'] == 'LONG TERM TWO WHEELER PACKAGE':
        return 'Private'
    else :
        return 'Motor Trade Insurance'
In [29]:
policies['Pooled_Products']=policies.apply(set_scr,axis=1)

  • Perform no operation . Try to Justify them with a factual backing . For Example : - Large Sum Insured is for an entire Motor Manufacturing company

  • Perform Statistical Test such as z-score , IQR , Quantile Methods to define a critical range of acceptable Sum Insured Amount.

Feature Engineering of the Event Type column¶

In [55]:
def set_scr3(hist_claims):
    if hist_claims['EVENT_TYPE'] in ('FLOOD/CYCLONE' , 'EARTHQUAKE/LANDSLIDE'):
        return 'Natural_Hazards'
    if hist_claims['EVENT_TYPE'] == 'FIRE':
        return 'Fire'
    if hist_claims['EVENT_TYPE'] == 'MALICIOUS DAMAGE':
        return 'Intentional_Damage'
    if hist_claims['EVENT_TYPE'] == 'THEFT ':
        return 'Theft'
    else :
        return 'Collision'
In [56]:
hist_claims['Pooled_Event_Type'] = hist_claims.apply(set_scr3,axis=1)

A customer is claiming 12 times ? Is it on the backs of multiple policies purchased ( 12 ) ? Or is it that 1 policy is being claimed 12 Times ? Let's find this out using a Ratio Called Risk Factor

Building a Customer Centric Data¶

In [76]:
X = df.groupby('CUSTOMER_IDENTIFIER')['POLICY_IDENTIFIER'].nunique()
Y = df.groupby('CUSTOMER_IDENTIFIER')['CLAIM_IDENTIFIER'].nunique()
Z = df.groupby('CUSTOMER_IDENTIFIER')['GENDER'].max()
A = df.groupby('CUSTOMER_IDENTIFIER')['DRIVING_EXPERIENCE'].max()
B = df.groupby('CUSTOMER_IDENTIFIER')['GWP'].sum()
C = df.groupby('CUSTOMER_IDENTIFIER')['TOTAL_CLAIM_PAID_AMOUNT'].sum()
D = df.groupby('CUSTOMER_IDENTIFIER')['Total_days_to_settle'].mean()
In [77]:
X_1 = pd.merge(X,Y,how='inner',left_index=True,right_index=True)
X_1 = pd.merge(X_1,Z,how='inner',left_index=True,right_index=True)
X_1 = pd.merge(X_1,A,how='inner',left_index=True,right_index=True)
X_1 = pd.merge(X_1,B,how='inner',left_index=True,right_index=True)
X_1 = pd.merge(X_1,C,how='inner',left_index=True,right_index=True)
X_1 = pd.merge(X_1,D,how='inner',left_index=True,right_index=True)

X_1['RiskFactor'] = X_1['CLAIM_IDENTIFIER']/X_1['POLICY_IDENTIFIER']
X_1['RiskFactor'] = X_1['RiskFactor'].round(0)
X_1.rename(columns={'POLICY_IDENTIFIER':'Total_Policies','CLAIM_IDENTIFIER':'Total_Claims'},inplace=True)

Risk Factor takes the value between 1 to 5

  • 1 implies the least Risky customer
  • 5 implies the most Risky customer
